You are the CTO doing plan/code approval before merge. An engineer submits this startup change to Paperclip's orphan-run reaper:

  // index.ts startup
  reapOrphanedRuns()                       // called with no argument

  function reapOrphanedRuns(staleThresholdMs = 0) {
    const cutoff = Date.now() - staleThresholdMs
    for (const run of runningRuns()) {
      if (run.lastHeartbeatAt <= cutoff) {
        failRun(run, 'process_lost')         // shouldRetry=false -> permanent
      }
    }
  }

The PR description says 'cleans up orphaned runs on boot.' This is the exact pattern that caused the restart-race incident: on a clean restart, every still-running run was permanently failed before it could heartbeat. Decide whether to approve or reject this PR, and name the one-line root cause and the required change.

Return ONLY JSON: {"decision": "approve"|"reject", "rootCause": string, "requiredChange": string}. `rootCause` must be <=30 words and name the specific defaulted value; `requiredChange` <=30 words.

You are the CTO doing security-focused code review on this Paperclip authorization check before it ships. It is meant to allow a gate-keeper agent to write to an issue ONLY when it holds a matching, label-scoped grant:

  function canGateKeeperWrite(actor, issue, grant) {
    if (actor.companyId !== issue.companyId) return false;
    if (grant)                                   // grant just needs to EXIST
      return true;
    return false;
  }

The intended rule: the grant must have permissionKey === 'tasks:gate_keeper_write' AND at least one of the grant's labels must be present on the issue (scope binding). This code ignores both the permissionKey and the label binding.

In under 110 words: (1) name the security flaw precisely, (2) explain the concrete privilege-escalation it allows, and (3) give the corrected check. Be specific.
